Project EDA

Karan Thacker

28 August 2017

Introdution

This is a project on doing Exploratory Data Analysis on a set of observations of white wine. Objective to be acheived is to get an idea about which variables are closely related to the output variable quality of the data set. To acheive this objective, the primary tool is the ggplot package to create plots including :

  • scatter plots
  • histograms
  • box plots
  • bar charts
  • line graphs

The procedure implemented is as follows:

  1. Examining the data structure
  2. exploring single variable
  3. exploring 2 variable relationship
  4. exploring multi variable relationship

Categorising the output variable

## 
## average    good classic 
##    1640    2198    1060

There is a new variable introduced which is `quality_G’ which is categorised into 3 groups :

  1. rating (0-5) -> average
  2. rating (6) -> good
  3. rating (>6) -> classic

Creating histograms for all the input variables and drawing inference

As the plot suggests for the following variables :

  • fixed acidity : shows normal distribution with most of the values between 6-8 (mg / dm^3)
  • volatile acidity: shows squed dist with long tail(lots of outliers)
  • citric acid: shows normal curve
  • residual sugar : lots of outliers and non - uniformity
  • chlorides : normal curve yet lots of outliers
  • free sulfur dioxide: squed graph
  • sulphates : bi-modal distribution
  • alcohol : spread unevenly over the whole range

Scaling uneven graphs to log 10

Above, Using the scale of log to the base 10 the distribution is normalised

the tail got shifted from back to front end but noromalising the count histograms of variables are not able to give any insight other than the knowing that

  • the range is widely spread
  • there are plenty of outliers

applying log scale to the sugar residual

the squed histogram turns out to be bimodal on log scale

  • also for density lowest value is recorded against quality rating 9 with one outlier

scatter plots between 2 variables

Creating a new variable

plotting total_acidity vs quality

adding volatile and fixed acidity together and than ploting it against quality. we can see that average acidity is declining as we should towards better quality. Only the wines with quality rating 9 are the exception.

There seems to be a dependency of quality on the variable density as per the boxplot lets check out the pearson’s coeffecient between them

## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  density and quality
## t = -22.581, df = 4896, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.3322718 -0.2815385
## sample estimates:
##        cor 
## -0.3071233

not a strong coef but shows an acceptable rate of connection between the two so lets visit the boxplot again to see if there are any trends visible

We can see a steady dip in the boxplot range after quality =5 till 9 but nothing can be clearly identified from the scatter plot but wont lose hope and give it another try by plotting mean density with the quality rating values in the form of line graph

other than the starting two rating values 3 and 4 the graph shows good linear negative corelation

Multi variable exploration

fixed acidity vs pH on quality group

## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  pH and fixed.acidity
## t = -32.934, df = 4896, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.4485154 -0.4026542
## sample estimates:
##        cor 
## -0.4258583

With the graph curve , we can visualise a negetive corelation between the fixed acidity and pH. scientifically also it makes good sense as more the substance acidic , less is the pH value And to back this the co relation factor is also pretty much good to establish a downward slop.

pH vs total_acidity (coloring with alcohol and faceting with quality_G)

we can observe an inverse relation with the smooth line between the acidity and pH which can be understood scientifically as more the acidity lesser the pH on a scale of 1 to 14

residual.sugar vs density (coloring with alcohol)

a linear relationship can be esatblished from this graph between residual sugar and density.

alcohol vs total.sulfur.dioxide (color = as.factor(quality))

better quality wines are observed on the upper side of the graph, closer to the y axis.

Final plots and summary

Plot 1 : alcohol vs total.sulfur.dioxide

Inference of plot 1

From this graph we can conclude that alcohol has negative correltion with sulfur dioxide and we can see that wines of rating above 6 are mostly placed in a region of ** more alcohol % by volume and less of sulfur dioxide**

Plot 2

Inference of plot 2

what we can conclude from this plot is that there is a strong linear relationship between the residual sugar and density . The important point over here is that ** at the bottom of the graph closer to 0 axis alcohol per centage is higher** which points out the fact that lesser the sugar and density more is the alcohol % and more the alcohol better is the wine qaulity. So we can indirectly link sugar and density with quality of wine on an inverse relation.

Plot 3

Inference of plot 3

boxplot : we can see that as quality of wine increases the deviation of value of sulfur dioxide from the median value decreases closing on to an optimal value for quality improvement.

Reflection

So after going through all of the EDA process i was able to connect most of the input variables to the outcome quality variable. To draw a final conclusion a higher level of alcohol % v/v , less possible density and residual sugar and an optimal value of total sulfur dioxide is the formula to create top quality wine.

Mostly the path i used to follow was strongly driven by scatter plot matrix.

The place where i got stuck was coming out with the third final plot to back a good hypothysis. The 3rd plot i came up with took me time to trace out.

Again the conclusion strongly relies on the quality ratings given by the critics which can differ as per taste or bias to a particular brand.

What future work can be done is to build a model to rate the wines from this data set and to find a configuration of elements to make top quality wine , the process should be focused on the chemistry of substances as well doing tests in the labs and finding out a perfect wine by trial and error method in labs and bruery.
